        <div class="verdict">✓ Updated April 2026</div>

        <p>Electrical contractors run two fundamentally different types of work: service and repair (residential panels, outlets, troubleshooting, small installs) and project-based installation (new construction wiring, commercial tenant improvements, large renovations). The software tools that work well for one often fall short for the other.</p>

        <h2>Software by electrical work type</h2>

        <h3>Residential electrical service work</h3>
        <p>For electrical contractors whose primary revenue is residential service calls — troubleshooting, panel upgrades, EV charger installations, outlet and switch work — the key software features are scheduling, dispatching, quoting, and invoicing. Fast quote turnaround and efficient scheduling of multiple technicians are the operational priorities.</p>

        <p><strong>Best picks:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Jobber ($69/mo):</strong> Clean scheduling, fast quote creation, online payment collection. Sufficient for most small residential electrical service businesses.</li>
          <li><strong>Contractor Foreman ($49/mo):</strong> More features including time tracking and job costing. Better for contractors who need both service and installation tools in one platform.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Commercial electrical subcontracting</h3>
        <p>Commercial electrical subcontractors — working under a GC, billing with AIA pay applications, managing projects over weeks or months — have completely different software needs. The key requirements are AIA billing (G702/G703), job costing against bid, change order tracking, and subcontractor compliance documentation.</p>

        <p><strong>Best pick: Knowify (~$149/mo)</strong> — The only platform in the mid-market specifically designed for commercial subcontractors. AIA billing, contract management, and job costing are all native. Integrates with QuickBooks for accounting.</p>

        <h3>Large residential electrical installation</h3>
        <p>Electrical contractors doing large residential projects — full home wiring for custom builds, complete electrical renovations — need project management tools that handle multi-week timelines, subcontractor coordination (low-voltage subs, inspection scheduling), and client communication.</p>

        <p><strong>Best pick: Buildertrend ($499/mo)</strong> — Full project management for complex residential installations. Scheduling, client portal, change orders, and document management in one platform.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>Buildertrend</strong> — When your electrical projects run for weeks and involve multiple trades.</p>
          <a href="https://www.buildertrend.com" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank" class="btn">Visit Buildertrend →</a>
        </div>

        <h2>Commercial electrical estimating: a separate category</h2>
        <p>Assembly-based electrical estimating — building bids from labor units, material databases, and electrical assemblies — requires specialized tools beyond what general construction software offers. If commercial estimating is a core part of your business, evaluate:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Accubid (Trimble):</strong> Industry standard for commercial electrical estimating. Complex but comprehensive.</li>
          <li><strong>McCormick Estimating:</strong> Strong alternative with good labor unit databases.</li>
          <li><strong>ConEst:</strong> Purpose-built for electrical estimating with built-in labor units.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>These pair with a separate PM platform (Knowify for subs, Buildertrend or Procore for larger operations) for actual project execution.</p>

        <h2>Key features for electrical contractors</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>AIA billing</strong> (if doing commercial work)</li>
          <li><strong>Job costing by cost code</strong> — labor, material, subcontractor separately</li>
          <li><strong>Change order tracking</strong> with customer or GC approval workflow</li>
          <li><strong>Scheduling</strong> — crew dispatch for service or multi-trade coordination for installs</li>
          <li><strong>Time tracking</strong> — field hours allocated to specific jobs and cost codes</li>
          <li><strong>Subcontractor compliance</strong> (certificates of insurance, lien waivers)</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile access</strong> — electricians need quick job notes and time entry from their phones</li>
        </ul>

